---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Base title="PIR for Ethereum State" description="Private Information Retrieval for Ethereum — scalable obliviousness primitives ensuring servers cannot learn what clients read.">
  <section class="section hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Private Information Retrieval for Ethereum State</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Cryptographic protocols that let clients query Ethereum data without revealing
        what they are reading.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" style="padding-top: 0;">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Every time a wallet checks a balance, verifies a transaction receipt, or reads
        contract storage from a remote server, the server learns exactly which records
        were accessed. This <strong>metadata leakage</strong> from read patterns enables
        <a href="https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/mev/">MEV extraction</a>,
        frontrunning, identity correlation, and surveillance. Even with encrypted
        connections, the <em>pattern</em> of accesses reveals user intent.
      </p>

      <h2>The Solution: Sharded PIR</h2>
      <p>
        Our <a href="https://notes.ethereum.org/U9xM4VOPR9isPK7lOZJUQg?view">sharded PIR design</a>
        segments Ethereum state into data slices — accounts, storage slots, contract code,
        transaction receipts — and serves each slice through a cryptographic PIR engine
        tuned for its size and access profile. The server processes encrypted queries and
        returns encrypted responses, never learning which record was requested.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Components</h2>
      <div class="grid grid--3" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Sidecar Architecture</h3>
          <p>
            A lightweight process that runs alongside any Ethereum execution client
            (Geth, Reth, etc.), indexing state into PIR-optimized databases and
            exposing a privacy-preserving query interface.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>GraphQL Interface</h3>
          <p>
            A familiar, developer-friendly API surface that mirrors
            <a href="https://ethereum.org/en/developers/docs/apis/json-rpc/">Ethereum's JSON-RPC</a>
            semantics while routing queries through PIR engines under the hood.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Scheme-Agnostic Design</h3>
          <p>
            The architecture abstracts over the underlying PIR scheme, allowing
            different engines to be swapped in as the field advances — no lock-in
            to a single cryptographic approach.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>PIR Schemes Under Evaluation</h2>
      <p>
        We are benchmarking and integrating multiple PIR schemes, each with different
        tradeoffs between communication cost, server computation, and preprocessing:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="https://0xalizk.github.io/plinko-arch/">Plinko</a> —
          A lattice-based scheme optimized for large databases with low communication
          overhead. Designed for Ethereum's account and storage tries.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://github.com/keewoolee/rms24">RMS24</a> —
          A scheme based on the Regev cryptosystem with matrix structure, offering
          a strong balance of server throughput and query compactness.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://igor53627.github.io/inspire-rs/protocol-visualization.html">insPIRe</a> —
          An interactive protocol visualization and implementation exploring
          puncturable pseudorandom functions for PIR.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Resources</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="https://notes.ethereum.org/U9xM4VOPR9isPK7lOZJUQg?view">
            Sharded PIR design note
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://0xalizk.github.io/PIR-Eng-Notes/">
            PIR Engineering Notes
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://hackmd.io/@keewoolee/SJyGoXCzZe">
            Practical PIR Guide
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://0xalizk.github.io/plinko-arch/">
            Plinko Architecture
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        <a href={`${base}/workstreams`}>&larr; Back to Workstreams</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .hero h1 {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .hero-subtitle {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    max-width: 640px;
  }
</style>
